---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Getting Started">

  <section class="gs-intro">
    <p class="gs-eyebrow">Setup Guide</p>
    <h1 class="gs-h1">Getting started</h1>
    <p class="gs-summary">
      The UX Intelligence tools let you ask Claude to review a page, analyse a competitor, or
      produce a design spec — and have the output automatically saved to this site. Everything
      runs through the <strong>Claude Code desktop app</strong>, which you'll set up in this guide.
      Setup takes around 30–45 minutes and only needs to be done once.
    </p>
    <div class="gs-notice">
      <strong>Why can't I just use Claude in my browser?</strong>
      The browser version of Claude can chat and analyse things, but it can't save files or
      publish anything to this site. The desktop app is what gives Claude permission to
      write reports, save screenshots, and send them live — which is the whole point.
    </div>
    <p class="gs-terminal-note">
      <strong>Developer?</strong> If you're comfortable with git and npm,
      <code>npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code</code> then <code>claude</code> from
      inside the repo folder is all you need. The rest of this guide covers the desktop app route.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PART 1 — GITHUB
  ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="gs-part">
    <div class="gs-part-header">
      <span class="gs-part-badge">Part 1</span>
      <h2 class="gs-part-title">GitHub</h2>
      <p class="gs-part-desc">GitHub is where the project files are stored online. You'll create an account, get access to the team's project, then download a copy to your computer.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Account -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">1</span>
        Create a GitHub account
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        GitHub is a platform for storing and sharing project files — think of it like a shared
        Google Drive, but for code and documents. The UX Intelligence site and all its reports
        live there. You'll need a free account to get access.
      </p>
      <a href="https://github.com/signup" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link">
        <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
        github.com/signup — create a free account
      </a>
      <p class="gs-body gs-body--note">
        Use your THG work email address — it makes it easy for the team admin to confirm who you
        are when they grant you access.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Repo access -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">2</span>
        Request access to the project
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        The project is private, so you'll need to be invited. Once you have your GitHub account,
        message <strong>Richard Gill</strong> and share your GitHub username (the name you chose
        when signing up). He'll add you to the project and GitHub will send you an email invite —
        open that email and click <strong>Accept invitation</strong>.
      </p>
      <div class="gs-repo-card">
        <div class="gs-repo-header">
          <span class="gs-repo-icon">◈</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-repo-org">THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds</p>
            <p class="gs-repo-name">ux-prototyping</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="gs-repo-desc">
          The UX Intelligence site and all its reports. Private — requires an invite from Richard Gill.
        </p>
        <a href="https://github.com/THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds/ux-prototyping" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-repo-link">
          View on GitHub →
        </a>
      </div>
      <div class="gs-tip">
        <strong>One extra step after accepting — don't skip this</strong>
        After you accept the invite, you need to authorise your account for the THG organisation.
        Go to <a href="https://github.com/settings/organizations" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-inline-link">github.com/settings/organizations</a>,
        find <strong>THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds</strong> in the list, and click <strong>Authorize</strong>.
        If you skip this, things will appear to work but saving reports will silently fail.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- GitHub Desktop + clone -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">3</span>
        Download the project to your computer
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Claude needs a copy of the project folder on your computer so it can save reports into it.
        <strong>GitHub Desktop</strong> is a free app that downloads the project for you and keeps
        it in sync with GitHub. You only need to do this once — after that, Claude handles
        everything automatically.
      </p>

      <div class="gs-substeps">

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">3a</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Download and install GitHub Desktop</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Download GitHub Desktop from the link below and open the installer. Follow the
              prompts to install it, then open the app.
            </p>
            <a href="https://desktop.github.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link">
              <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
              desktop.github.com — download GitHub Desktop
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">3b</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Sign in to GitHub Desktop</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              When GitHub Desktop opens for the first time, you'll see a welcome screen with
              a few options. Click <strong>Sign in to GitHub.com</strong>. A browser window
              will open — sign in using the GitHub account you created in step 1, then click
              <strong>Authorize desktop</strong> when prompted. Switch back to GitHub Desktop
              once it's done.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">3c</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Choose "Clone a Repository from the Internet"</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Back in GitHub Desktop you'll see a screen with three options — click
              <strong>Clone a Repository from the Internet</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">3d</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Enter the repository URL</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              A window will appear with three tabs at the top: <em>GitHub.com</em>,
              <em>GitHub Enterprise</em>, and <em>URL</em>. Click the <strong>URL</strong> tab.
              Then paste the following address into the <strong>Repository URL</strong> field:
            </p>
            <div class="gs-copyblock">
              <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="repo-url">https://github.com/THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds/ux-prototyping</pre>
              <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
                navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('repo-url').innerText);
                this.textContent = 'Copied!';
                setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
              ">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Under <strong>Local Path</strong>, choose where to save the folder on your computer.
              Your <strong>Documents</strong> folder is a good choice — somewhere easy to find.
              Then click <strong>Clone</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">3e</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Find the folder on your computer</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Once cloning finishes, go to <strong>Repository → Show in Finder</strong> (Mac) or
              <strong>Show in Explorer</strong> (Windows). This opens the project folder — keep
              that window handy, because you'll need to point Claude Code at it in Part 3.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PART 2 — GIT
  ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="gs-part">
    <div class="gs-part-header">
      <span class="gs-part-badge">Part 2</span>
      <h2 class="gs-part-title">Git</h2>
      <p class="gs-part-desc">Git is a background tool that Claude uses to save and sync reports automatically. It needs to be installed separately — this only takes a few minutes.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">4</span>
        Install Git
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Git is a tool that tracks changes to files and handles syncing them with GitHub. Claude
        uses it behind the scenes every time it saves a report — you won't interact with it
        directly, but it needs to be installed on your computer before Claude can do its job.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-body gs-body--note">
        <strong>Not sure if you already have it?</strong> If you've used a developer tool or
        the terminal before, Git may already be installed. Either way, following the steps below
        won't cause any problems.
      </p>

      <div class="gs-substeps">

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">Mac</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Mac — install Git</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Open the <strong>Terminal</strong> app — press <strong>⌘ Space</strong>, type
              <em>Terminal</em>, and press Enter. Then copy and paste the command below into
              the Terminal window and press Enter:
            </p>
            <div class="gs-copyblock">
              <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="git-install-mac">xcode-select --install</pre>
              <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
                navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('git-install-mac').innerText);
                this.textContent = 'Copied!';
                setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
              ">Copy</button>
            </div>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              One of two things will happen:
            </p>
            <ul class="gs-outcome-list">
              <li>
                <strong>A pop-up window appears</strong> — minimise any open windows so you can
                see it, then click <strong>Install</strong>. It takes 5–10 minutes. Once it
                finishes, you're done — close Terminal and move on.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>The terminal shows a message saying "already installed"</strong> — that's
                good news. Git is already on your computer. Close Terminal and move on.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">Win</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Windows — install Git</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Download the Git installer from the link below, open it, and click through the
              installer accepting all the default options.
            </p>
            <a href="https://git-scm.com/download/win" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link">
              <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
              git-scm.com/download/win — Git for Windows
            </a>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Once the installer finishes, Git is ready. You don't need to open or configure anything further.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PART 3 — CLAUDE DESKTOP
  ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="gs-part">
    <div class="gs-part-header">
      <span class="gs-part-badge">Part 3</span>
      <h2 class="gs-part-title">Claude Desktop</h2>
      <p class="gs-part-desc">Install the Claude desktop app, point it at the project folder you downloaded, then connect it to Chrome and GitHub so it can browse pages and save reports.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Install app -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">5</span>
        Install the Claude desktop app
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Claude is made by a company called Anthropic. The desktop app is a more powerful version
        of Claude that can access files on your computer — which is what lets it save reports to
        the project folder. Download it from the link below and sign in or create an account.
      </p>
      <p class="gs-body gs-body--note">
        <strong>Who pays for this?</strong> You'll need a Claude Pro subscription ($20/month)
        to use Claude Code. Check with your team lead first — THG may have team seats or an
        expenses process so you don't need to pay personally.
      </p>
      <a href="https://claude.ai/download" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link">
        <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
        claude.ai/download — download the desktop app
      </a>
      <div class="gs-tip">
        <strong>Already use Claude.ai in your browser?</strong>
        You already have an account — just use the same email and password to sign in to the
        desktop app. No need to create anything new.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Open repo -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">6</span>
        Point Claude at the project folder
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Once the app is open, you need to tell Claude where the project folder is on your
        computer. This is what gives it permission to read and save files inside it.
      </p>

      <div class="gs-substeps">

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">6a</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Switch to Claude Code mode</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Open the Claude desktop app. At the top of the window, look for a dropdown or
              menu that says <strong>Claude Code</strong> — click it to switch into that mode.
              It looks similar to a normal chat, but now Claude has access to files on your machine.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">6b</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Select the project folder</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              Claude Code will ask you to choose a project folder. Navigate to the
              <strong>ux-prototyping</strong> folder you downloaded in step 3 — it'll be
              wherever you saved it (for example, inside your Documents folder). Select it
              and click <strong>Open</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-substep">
          <span class="gs-substep-label">6c</span>
          <div>
            <p class="gs-substep-title">Check it's working</p>
            <p class="gs-substep-body">
              In the chat box, type a forward slash: <strong>/</strong>
              A list of commands should appear. If you can see it, Claude Code is connected
              to the project folder and ready to use.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Connectors -->
    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">7</span>
        Connect Chrome and GitHub
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Two add-ons extend what Claude can do: a Chrome extension lets Claude open and read
        web pages, and a GitHub connection lets Claude save reports directly to the project.
        Both install in a couple of minutes.
      </p>

      <div class="gs-plugin-card">
        <div class="gs-plugin-header">
          <span class="gs-plugin-badge gs-plugin-badge--chrome">Chrome</span>
          <h3 class="gs-plugin-name">Claude browser extension</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="gs-plugin-desc">
          This connects Claude to your Chrome browser so it can open web pages, scroll through
          them, and take screenshots. Without it, the UX Review and Competitor Analysis tools
          won't work — they need to actually visit the pages they're reviewing.
        </p>
        <div class="gs-plugin-steps">
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">1</span> Install the extension from the Chrome Web Store:</p>
          <a href="https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/claude/pnaoflhkifljdmpmollaobhbknaeeafh" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="gs-external-link gs-external-link--sm">
            <span class="gs-external-icon">↗</span>
            Claude extension — Chrome Web Store
          </a>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">2</span> After installing, click the Claude icon that appears in your Chrome toolbar (top right of the browser). Sign in using the same email and password you use for the Claude desktop app.</p>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">3</span> Keep Chrome open whenever you're using Claude Code — the connection only works while Chrome is running.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="gs-plugin-card">
        <div class="gs-plugin-header">
          <span class="gs-plugin-badge gs-plugin-badge--github">GitHub</span>
          <h3 class="gs-plugin-name">GitHub connection</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="gs-plugin-desc">
          This lets Claude save and upload reports to GitHub automatically, so they appear on
          the site. Without it, Claude can still write files locally but won't be able to
          publish them.
        </p>
        <div class="gs-plugin-steps">
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">1</span> In the Claude desktop app, click the <strong>+</strong> button at the bottom of the chat box and choose <strong>Plugins</strong> from the menu that appears.</p>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">2</span> Find <strong>GitHub</strong> in the list and click the <strong>+</strong> button next to it.</p>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">3</span> A browser window will open asking you to authorise Claude. Sign in with your GitHub account (the one from step 1) and click <strong>Authorize</strong>. When asked about organisation access, approve <strong>THG-AltitudeSiteBuilds</strong>.</p>
          <p class="gs-plugin-step"><span class="gs-plugin-step-num">4</span> Done — you only need to do this once. The connection stays active across sessions.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="gs-body gs-body--note" style="margin-top: 12px; margin-bottom: 0;">
          If GitHub doesn't appear in the plugin list, it may not be included in your current Claude plan.
          Claude can still save reports without it, but contact Richard Gill if you're having trouble publishing.
        </p>
      </div>

    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PART 4 — AGENT SKILLS
  ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="gs-part">
    <div class="gs-part-header">
      <span class="gs-part-badge">Part 4</span>
      <h2 class="gs-part-title">Install the tools</h2>
      <p class="gs-part-desc">The UX Intelligence tools are loaded into Claude one at a time. This takes about 2 minutes each and only needs to be done once — after that they're always available.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">8</span>
        Load each tool into Claude
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        Claude's UX Intelligence tools — like the UX Review, Competitor Analysis, and Design QA —
        are stored as instruction files in the project folder. You need to register each one with
        Claude so it knows they exist. You do this by typing a special command and pasting a short
        prompt. Claude reads the instruction file and saves the tool — it only takes a minute each.
      </p>
      <div class="gs-callout gs-callout--info">
        <strong>Do these one at a time.</strong> In Claude Code (with the ux-prototyping folder open),
        type <strong>/skill-creator</strong> in the chat, then paste the prompt for the first tool
        below and press Enter. Wait for Claude to finish, then repeat for the next one.
      </div>

      <div class="gs-skill-install-list" style="margin-top: 20px;">

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/myprotein-ux-review</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">UX Review agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-1">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/myprotein-ux-review/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-1').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/competitor-analysis</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">Competitor Analysis agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-2">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/competitor-analysis/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-2').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/design-qa</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">Design QA agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-3">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/design-qa/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-3').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/myprotein-prep-agent</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">Project Prep agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-4">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/myprotein-prep-agent/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-4').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="gs-skill-install-item">
          <div class="gs-skill-install-header">
            <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/figma-engineering-handover</code>
            <span class="gs-skill-label">Engineering Handover agent</span>
          </div>
          <div class="gs-copyblock">
            <pre class="gs-code gs-code--wrap" id="skill-prompt-5">Please create a new skill using the content from this file: src/skills/user/figma-engineering-handover/SKILL.md</pre>
            <button class="gs-copy-btn" onclick="
              navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById('skill-prompt-5').innerText);
              this.textContent = 'Copied!';
              setTimeout(() => this.textContent = 'Copy', 2000);
            ">Copy</button>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="gs-section">
      <h3 class="gs-section-heading">
        <span class="gs-step-badge">9</span>
        Confirm all five tools are available
      </h3>
      <p class="gs-body">
        In the Claude Code chat box, type <strong>/</strong> — a list of available commands will
        appear. You should see all five tools in the list:
      </p>
      <div class="gs-skill-list">
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/myprotein-ux-review</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">UX Review</span>
        </div>
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/competitor-analysis</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">Competitor Analysis</span>
        </div>
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/design-qa</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">Design QA</span>
        </div>
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/myprotein-prep-agent</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">Project Prep</span>
        </div>
        <div class="gs-skill-row">
          <code class="gs-skill-cmd">/figma-engineering-handover</code>
          <span class="gs-skill-label">Engineering Handover</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="gs-body" style="margin-top: 12px;">
        If one is missing, repeat step 8 for that tool only.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── First run ────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="gs-section">
    <h2 class="gs-section-heading">
      <span class="gs-step-badge">10</span>
      You're ready — run your first review
    </h2>
    <p class="gs-body">
      Type the command below into Claude Code, replacing the URL with any Myprotein page
      you want to review, and press Enter:
    </p>
    <pre class="gs-code">/myprotein-ux-review https://www.myprotein.com/sports-nutrition/impact-whey-protein/10530943.html</pre>
    <p class="gs-body">
      Claude will open the page in Chrome, read through it, write up a structured UX report,
      and save it to GitHub automatically. The whole process takes a few minutes — you'll see
      it working in the chat as it goes.
    </p>
    <div class="gs-tip">
      <strong>One manual step at the end — publishing to the site</strong>
      After Claude saves the report, it needs to be published to the live site manually. This
      is done through <strong>Altitude</strong> — THG's internal publishing platform. If you
      have Altitude access, log in and trigger a deploy. If not, ask Richard Gill to publish
      it for you — just let him know when Claude has finished saving the report.
    </div>

    <p class="gs-body" style="margin-top: 8px;">
      See the <a href="/agents/ux-review" class="gs-inline-link">tool guides</a> for a full
      walkthrough of each tool, what to expect, and how to handle any issues.
    </p>
